{"title_page": "A. Theodore Eastman", "text_new": "{{short description|American Espiscopal bishop}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Bishop\n| honorific_prefix = The Right Reverend\n| name             = Albert Theodore Eastman\n| honorific_suffix = D.D., L H.D.\n| title            = [[Episcopal Diocese of Maryland|Bishop of Maryland]]\n| image            = Headshot - A Theodore Eastman.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]]\n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = [[Episcopal Diocese of Maryland|Maryland]]\n| see              = \n| elected          = \n| term             = 1986-1994\n| quashed          = <!-- or | retired = -->\n| predecessor      = [[David Leighton]]\n| successor        = [[Robert W. Ihloff]]\n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = 1954\n| ordained_by      = [[Karl M. Block]]\n| consecration     = June 26, 1982\n| consecrated_by   = [[John Allin]]\n| rank             = \n| laicized         = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1928|11|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[San Mateo, California]], United States\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2018|04|26|1928|11|20}}\n| death_place      = [[Arlington, Virginia]], United States\n| buried           = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| religion         = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = Carl John Eastman & Inette Nordeen\n| spouse           = Sarah Virginia Tice <small>''(m. June 13, 1953)''</small>\n| children         = Sarah Eastman Reks, Anne Eastman Rosenbaum, Andrew Tice Eastman\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = Coadjutor Bishop of Maryland <small>''(1982-1986)''</small>\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| other            = \n}}\n'''Albert Theodore \"Ted\" Eastman''' (November 20, 1928 \u2013 April 26, 2018)<ref name=\"WP\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/a-theodore-eastman-bishop-of-the-episcopal-diocese-of-maryland-dies-at-89/2018/04/28/cb480b24-4a38-11e8-9072-f6d4bc32f223_story.html |title=A. Theodore Eastman, bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of Maryland, dies at 89 |first=Ellie |last=Silverman |date=April 28, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180429100654/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/a-theodore-eastman-bishop-of-the-episcopal-diocese-of-maryland-dies-at-89/2018/04/28/cb480b24-4a38-11e8-9072-f6d4bc32f223_story.html?noredirect=on |archive-date=2018-04-29 |url-status=live }}</ref> was an American prelate who served as the twelfth [[Episcopal Diocese of Maryland|Bishop of Maryland]] from 1986 to 1994.\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nEastman was born on November 20, 1928 in [[San Mateo, California]], the son of Carl John Eastman and Inette Nordeen, immigrants from Sweden. He attended public school in Burlingame, California. He studied at [[Haverford College]] from where he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in 1950. He then graduated with a [[Master of Divinity]] from [[Virginia Theological Seminary]] in 1953. The latter also awarded him with a [[Doctor of Divinity]] in 1983. He also received a [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] from [[Seminary of the Southwest|Episcopal Theological Seminary]] in 1982 and another [[Doctor of Divinity]] from [[St. Mary's Seminary and University]] in 1994.<ref>[https://www.episcopalnewsservice.org/2018/04/27/r-i-p-the-rt-rev-a-theodore-eastman-retired-bishop-of-maryland/ \"RIP: The Rt. Rev. A. Theodore Eastman, retired bishop of Maryland\"], ''Episcopal News Service'', New York, 27 April 2018. Retrieved on 28 November 2019.</ref>\n\n==Ordained Ministry==\nEastman was ordained deacon on July 15, 1953 in [[Grace Cathedral, San Francisco]], by the hands of [[Henry H. Shires]], Suffragan Bishop of California.<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 9, 1953 |title=Ordinations |journal=[[The Living Church]] |volume=127 |issue=6 |pages=14}}</ref> He was then ordained priest in 1954 by the hands of [[Karl M. Block]], Diocesan Bishop of California. In 1953 he became vicar of Trinity Church in [[Gonzales, California]], and concurrently served as chaplain of [[Soledad State Prison]] from 1954\u20131956. In 1956 he became executive secretary of the Overseas Mission Society of the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church of the United States]] in Washington, DC. During his assignment with the Overseas Mission Society, he served short-term pastorates in [[Tokyo|Tokyo, Japan]], [[Mexico City|Mexico City, Mexico]], and [[Vienna|Vienna, Austria]]. In 1968 he served a year as consultant to the House of Bishops, before becoming rector of the Church of Mediator in [[Allentown, Pennsylvania]] in 1969. In 1973 he became rector of [[St. Alban's Episcopal Church (Washington, D.C.)|St Alban's Church]] in [[Washington D.C.]], where he remained till 1982.<ref>[https://livingchurch.org/2018/04/27/bishop-eastman-dies-at-89/ \"Bishop Eastman Dies at 89\"], ''[[The Living Church]]'', Milwaukee, 27 April 2018. Retrieved on 28 November 2019.</ref> He served two terms as a Trustee of the [[Virginia Theological Seminary]] from 1962 until 1967.\n\n== Educator ==\nIn 1963, Eastman was a visiting fellow at the [[Seminary of the Southwest|Episcopal Theological Seminary of the Southwest]]. He also was a guest lecturer at the [[Episcopal Divinity School]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], in 1964, and at the College of Preachers in 1966.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://episcopalchurch.org/library/glossary/college-preachers|title=College of Preachers|date=2012-05-22|website=Episcopal Church|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> As bishop, Eastman chaired the Council of the College of Preachers from 1978 until 1982, where he was also a fellow. He chaired the Steering Committee of the College of Bishops, an innovative three-year program of formation for newly elected bishops, hosted by the General Theological Seminary in New York, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegeforbishops.org/|title=College for Bishops|website=College for Bishops|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Bishop==\nEastman was elected [[Coadjutor bishop|Coadjutor Bishop]] of the [[Episcopal Diocese of Maryland]] on March 20, 1982, during a special diocesan convention in Trinity Church, [[Towson, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 25, 1982 |title=Coadjutor Elected in Maryland |journal=[[The Living Church]] |volume=184 |issue= |pages=6}}</ref> He was [[consecration|consecrated]] on June 26, 1982 by Presiding Bishop [[John Allin]], assisted by [[David Leighton]], Bishop of Maryland, and [[Harry Lee Doll]], former Bishop of Maryland, in [[Washington National Cathedral]]. He succeeded as [[diocesan bishop]] 1986 and retired in 1994. During his tenure as bishop, he served in other capacities in the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]], notably as Vice Chair of the Standing Committee on World Mission and Chair of the [[Episcopal Relief & Development|Presiding Bishop's Fund for World Relief]]. His work in mission and ecumenism took him to more three dozen countries in [[Africa]], [[Asia]], [[Latin America]], [[Europe]], and the [[Middle East]].\n\nBetween 1991 and 1994 he also served as chairman of the Standing Commission on Ecumenical Relations of the Episcopal Church. From 1984 until 1992, he co-chaired the Anglican-Roman Catholic Consultation in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arcusa.church/|title=Anglican-Roman Catholic Theological Consultation in the United States of America (ARCUSA)|website=arcusa.church|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Later he was also installed as a member of the [[Washington National Cathedral]] [[Cathedral chapter|chapter]].\n\nHe was a Member of the Board of Trustees of Listening Hearts Ministries,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://listeninghearts.org/|title=Listening Hearts Ministries \u2014 Teaching people the practice of spiritual discernment through prayerful listening in supportive communities.|website=listeninghearts.org|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> a [[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]]-based organization that provides training and resource for spiritual discernment.\n\n== Retirement ==\nIn 1998, Bishop Eastman was asked to serve as [[Provost (religion)|Provost]] of the [[Washington National Cathedral]], during the sabbatical leave of then Dean [[Nathan D. Baxter]]. He became the Executive Vice President and later the Senior Executive Director of [[Protestant Episcopal Cathedral Foundation]]. After the departure of Dean Baxter following his consecration as the 10th Bishop of the [[Episcopal Diocese of Central Pennsylvania]], Eastman was called to serve as [[Vicar]] of the [[Washington National Cathedral]] from 2003\u20132005. During that time among other duties he led the planning and participated in the [[Death and state funeral of Ronald Reagan|State Funeral]] for [[Ronald Reagan|President Ronald Reagan]] delivering the benediction. Eastman also participated in the National Prayer Service on January 21, 2005, following the inauguration of [[George W. Bush|President George W. Bush]].\n\nHe died on April 26, 2018, in a hospital in [[Arlington, Virginia]], due to complications related to [[Parkinson's disease]].\n\n== Hymns ==\nEastman wrote the lyrics to the following hymns during his lifetime.\n\n<u>Holy and Creative Spirit</u>, tune by the Reverend Richard Townsend Carrol Peard, 1975\n\n<u>Hail Thee Festival Day</u>, Christmas edition, tune by Ralph Vaughn Williams, 1906\n\n<u>Mighty God of Cosmic Splendor</u>, tune by Gary Davison, 1999\n\n== Published Works ==\nAssociate Editor, <u>Overseas Mission Review</u>, 1957-1968\n\n<u>Letters from the Rim of Asia</u>, [[National Council of Churches|The National Council]], 1962\n\n<u>Christian Responsibility in One World (The Kellogg Lectures)</u>, [[Seabury Books|Seabury]], 1965\n\n<u>Missions: \u201cIn\u201d or Out?</u>, Friendship Press, 1967\n\n<u>New Life in a Congregation</u>, Audenshaw Foundation, 1969\n\n<u>Chosen and Sent: Calling the Church to Mission</u>, [[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]], 1971\n\n<u>The Baptizing Community: Christian Initiation and the Local Congregation</u>, [[Morehouse Publishing]], 1990\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://ns.cathedral.org/staff/PE-3TSUM-010I1D.shtml National Cathedral staff biography]{{dead link|date=September 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* ''Episcopal Clerical Directory'', 2015\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eastman, A. Theodore}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bishops of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Espiscopal bishop}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Bishop\n| honorific_prefix = The Right Reverend\n| name             = Albert Theodore Eastman\n| honorific_suffix = D.D., L H.D.\n| title            = [[Episcopal Diocese of Maryland|Bishop of Maryland]]\n| image            = Headshot - A Theodore Eastman.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]]\n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = [[Episcopal Diocese of Maryland|Maryland]]\n| see 